======================================================================
CONSTRAINT STRUCTURE THEOREM FOR PALEY TOURNAMENTS
opus-2026-03-13-S71b — Comprehensive Summary
======================================================================

For P_p with p ≡ 3 mod 4, m = (p-1)/2, QR = quadratic residues.

SETUP:
  A d-diff-seq is (s_1,...,s_d) ∈ QR^d with all partial sums distinct.
  Interior face i (1 ≤ i ≤ d-1) merges s_i + s_{i+1} and is "junk"
  when s_i + s_{i+1} ∉ QR.

  The constraint matrix C_d has:
    - Rows: junk (d-1)-tuples (faces not in A_{d-1})
    - Columns: d-diff-seqs in A_d
    - Entry: sum of (-1)^i over all faces of σ that equal the row tuple

  Omega_d = ker(C_d), so dim(Omega_d) = |A_d| - rank(C_d).

======================================================================
BLOCK STRUCTURE
======================================================================

THEOREM (Block Diagonality): The junk face rows partition into (d-1)
blocks indexed by face index i ∈ {1,...,d-1}:

  Block i: junk faces from face i have the (d-1)-tuple type signature
    (QR,...,QR, NQR, QR,...,QR)
    where position i-1 is in NQR and all other positions are in QR.

  These blocks are PAIRWISE DISJOINT since QR ∩ NQR = ∅.

PROOF (sketch):
  Face i of (s_1,...,s_d) is the (d-1)-tuple obtained by replacing
  (s_i, s_{i+1}) with s_i + s_{i+1}. The entries at positions ≠ i-1
  retain their original QR values (being elements of the diff-seq).
  Position i-1 has value s_i + s_{i+1} ∈ NQR (junk condition).

  For blocks i and j (i ≠ j), position i-1 must be in NQR for block i
  but in QR for block j (since it's an original QR entry in block j).
  Hence the blocks are disjoint. ∎

======================================================================
DEGREE 2: PROVED (HYP-678)
======================================================================

  |A_2|/p = m²
  Blocks: 1 (face 1 only). Rows: NQR values r.
  N(r) = (m+1)/2 for r ∈ NQR (Jacobi sum J(χ,χ) = 1).
  rank(C_2) = m (one per NQR value, each block trivially rank 1).
  Omega_2/p = m² - m = m(m-1).

======================================================================
DEGREE 3: PROVED (HYP-679)
======================================================================

  |A_3|/p = m(m-1)p/2
  Blocks: 2 (faces 1 and 2).
    Block 1: (NQR, QR) — m(m-1) rows
    Block 2: (QR, NQR) — m(m-1) rows
  Signs: face 1 = -1, face 2 = +1 (OPPOSITE signs).
  Each block has full row rank = m(m-1).
  Blocks don't couple (opposite signs → no cancellation).
  rank(C_3) = 2m(m-1).
  Omega_3/p = m(m-1)(p-4)/2.

======================================================================
DEGREE 4: PROVED (HYP-680)
======================================================================

  Blocks: 3 (faces 1, 2, 3).
    Block 1: (NQR, QR, QR) — signs: -1
    Block 2: (QR, NQR, QR) — signs: +1
    Block 3: (QR, QR, NQR) — signs: -1

  Each block individually has FULL ROW RANK.

  INTER-BLOCK COUPLING:
  Blocks 1 and 3 have the SAME SIGN (-1).
  Columns hitting both create "parallel" entries.

  The coupling decomposes into m² sub-blocks indexed by (r, r') ∈ NQR²:
    Sub-block (r, r'): connects
      B₁ rows {(r, u, v) : u+v = r'} (N(r') = (m+1)/2 rows)
      B₃ rows {(s, t, r') : s+t = r} (N(r) = (m+1)/2 rows)
    via N(r)·N(r') = ((m+1)/2)² columns.

    This is a COMPLETE BIPARTITE graph.
    Rank = N(r) + N(r') - 1 = m.
    Nullity = 1.

  Sub-blocks are row-disjoint → nullity = m² × 1 = m².

  Block 2 (opposite sign) doesn't contribute to null space.

  rank(C_4) = (total junk rows) - m².

======================================================================
DEGREE 5+: PARTIALLY ANALYZED
======================================================================

  Blocks: (d-1) blocks with signs (-1)^1, (-1)^2, ..., (-1)^{d-1}.
  Same-sign pairs: {(i,j) : i ≡ j mod 2}.
  Each pair contributes coupling nullity.

  At d=5: same-sign pairs (1,3), (2,4), (1,5 doesn't exist).
  HOWEVER: the nullity is MORE than 2m² — additional contributions
  from columns hitting 3 or 4 blocks simultaneously.

  VERIFIED:
    d=5, P_7:  nullity = 33
    d=5, P_11: nullity = 250
    d=6, P_7:  nullity = 42
    d=6, P_11: nullity = 1620

  No simple closed formula found yet.

